- Updated the RPC protocols (forgot to do the reality test! It is impossible to resolve named parameters). - StreamedRPCProtocol now have 2 variants of parseRequest(...) one taking an InputStream and one taking a parameter Map. The latter for HTTP transports. - Added StreamedHTTPProtocol. This extends StreamedRPCProtocol and implies that any returned RPCError is actually an HTTPError subclass providing an http status code. This for a bit better interaction between HTTP transports and protocols wanting to support HTTP status codes rather than writing their own response. A REST type protocol is still not fully possible since we are still calling OSGi services by service class and method. - APSExternalProtocolHTTPTransportProvider now supports ?params=value for GET. - new JSONHTTP protocol tries to be as HTTP friendly as possible talking JSON and for GET can handle parameters with "?params=param:...:param" but only with primitives and String parameters. For POST and PUT a JSON array of objects or primitives can be sent as parameters.
Added System.out.println(...) and e.printStackTrace() if no logger has been provided for when onService* throws exceptions.

Dumb bug that was damn difficult to find have now been fixed. I apparently got interrupted while implementing setDataTypeClass(...) and never finished implementing it resulting in getDataTypeClass() returning null and causing an NPE (this should never be null!).

Added APSActivator to aps-tools-lib with a set of annotations for auto registering services and injecting tracked services and other instances. This activator must be specified as bundle activator for it to be used.

I stupidly got a dependency on aps-apis for aps-tools-lib! This has now been removed. aps-tools-lib should be free of any non standard dependency so that it can be used as is in any OSGi framework even if nothing else from APS is used.
aps-openjpa-provider now scans currently available bundles for persistence.xml on startup, allowing "client" bundles to be started before this.

APSActivator can now register several instances of services.

Added required=true on @APSOSGiService with the effect of delayed publishing of services having required=true dependencies until all those dependencies are available. If any of those leaves long enough for a timeout then the service will be unpublished until the dependent service becomes available again. The bundle itself never changes any state due to this.
Renamed the APSActivator annotations by removing APS prefix.
Added new Tuple...Tuple4 classes for imitation of tuples in other languages.
- Debugged and added functionality to APSActivator. - APSSimpleUserServiceProvider now uses the APSActivator using instance factory.

- The MultiBundleClassLoader of APSOpenJPAProvider has now been moved to APSToolsLib. - APSOpenJPAProvider now uses new features in MultiBundleClassLoader to extends the JPA framework classpath to clients of clients to more easily be able to provide JDBC drivers.

APSActivator now supports 2 modes: Activator mode where it just scans all the bundles classes and manages any annotations. This is achieved by using the default constructor of APSActivator.
The second mode is the existing instances mode. This requires the constructor where you pass at least one instance to the constructor. Calls to addManagedInstance(instance) can also be done before start(BundleContext) is done. In this case it will just add the provided instances as managed instances, and then scan the bundle classes skipping any class that already has a provided managed instance. This way web-container created instances like servlets can be managed by the activator also. In a WAB you mostly want to inject tracked services, but it is possible to provide service instances also.
APSVaadinOSGiApplication and APSOSGiSupport (for servlets, etc) creates an APSActivator and adds itself/its caller to it thus handling annotations.
Debugged usage of APSActivator annotations in WAB application. It turns out that you can only get annotations from a class if you import the package of the annotations :-).

APSGroups now supports both multicast and TCP transports which can be defined in configuration.

Now added a config for the aps-config-service-provider. The config allows to enable/disable synchronization of config and also specify a group name where synchronization will only be done to the members of the same group thus allowing several groups on the same subnet with multicast transport.
Updated the version number in the README.md file.
APSActivator now threads the whole startup management of a @APSOSGIServiceProvider(threadedStart=true) and thus avoids a deadlock if instance factory does a service call to non started service.

- New APSMessageService API. - New APSSyncService API. - New APSNetTimeService API. - New APSSyncService provider using APSGroupsService. - New APSNetTimeService provider using APSGroupsService. - Synchronizer in APSConfigService provider now uses the new APSSyncService rather than APSGroupsService. - All this in preparation for providing providing an APSMessageServcie provider based on RabbitMQ, and an alternative APSSyncService provider using APSMessageService.
Fixed bug in APSGroups that ignored new members being announced.
- It is now possible to config queues. - Startup is now threaded so that RabbitMQ connection can be made from config without deadlocking waiting for config to become available.
